<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-697-844  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 697 844.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  June 1990 p11(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Document scanning: worth a closer look? (includes la relatedarticle on scanning suppliers and their prices)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Neesham, Claire.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Advances in two-dimensional scanning of technical drawings andother hardcopy engineering design documents has made thetechnology an accepted tool for editing and archiving documents incomputer-aided design (CAD) systems, though many improvements arestill needed.andP;  Storing drawings digitally offers severaladvantages, including reduced space demand, easy access andrevision, and immunity to deterioration.andP;  Scanning enables therapid entry of large amounts of data (drawings), but itssuccessful use requires suitable scanning, computer and storagehardware, plus scanning, recognition and editing software.andP;  Theseinclude a way of displaying scanned data as raster images, rasterediting software, text recognition systems, data base for storingimages and a way of transferring images into a CAD system (andvector format).andP;  Problems in 2D scanning technology are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Scanning DevicesTechnologyDocument Management SystemsSystem DevelopmentRequirements AnalysisCost Benefit Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>